Title: THEVENIN DECOMPOSITION 1 AND LARGE-SCALE OPTIMIZATION  
Author: by Dimitri P. Bertsekas 
Keyword: optimization, decomposition, circuit theory, network ows.  
Note: October 1993 LIDS-P-2204 Appears in J.O.T.A., Vol. 89, 1996, pp. 1-15.  
Abstract: Thevenin's theorem, one of the most celebrated results of electric circuit theory, provides a two-parameter characterization of the behavior of an arbitrarily large circuit, as seen from two of its terminals. We interpret the theorem as a sensitivity result in an associated minimum energy/network ow problem, and we abstract its main idea to develop a decomposition method for convex quadratic programming problems with linear equality constraints, such as those arising in a variety of contexts such as Newton's method, interior point methods, and least squares estimation. Like Thevenin's theorem, our method is particularly useful in problems involving a system consisting of several subsystems, connected to each other with a small number of coupling variables. 
